 I.  SUMMARY                                                      9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
     The cross section data file for neutron reactions with 241Am 9543 1451
 has been reevaluated over the incident neutron energy range from 9543 1451
 0.01 to 30 MeV.  The evaluation is in ENDF-6 format.  Details of 9543 1451
 the analysis are given in the sections that follow.  Some        9543 1451
 general features of the work are:                                9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
 1.  The ENDF/B-VI n + 241Am resonance parameters were adopted at 9543 1451
 neutron energies below 30 keV, suitably joined with the results  9543 1451
 of the present analysis at 30 keV.                               9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
 2.  A coupled-channel optical model potential was developed from 9543 1451
 analyses of nearby actinides that is consistent with             9543 1451
 measurements of the n + 241Am neutron total cross section.  This 9543 1451
 potential was used to calculate the neutron total cross section, 9543 1451
 elastic and inelastic scattering cross sections and angular      9543 1451
 distributions, and reaction cross sections and transmission      9543 1451
 coefficients for a theoretical analysis of the reaction          9543 1451
 channels.  The direct cross sections from the coupled-channel    9543 1451
 analysis were combined with compound nucleus calculations at     9543 1451
 lower energies and with preequilibrium theory calculations at    9543 1451
 higher energies.  Angular distributions for the first 40 excited 9543 1451
 states of 241Am were obtained from the direct, compound-nucleus, 9543 1451
 and preequilibrium calculations, and energy-angle correlated     9543 1451
 distributions are provided for all continuum neutrons.           9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
 3.  The evaluated fission and total cross sections were obtained 9543 1451
 by adjusting the theoretical cross sections as needed to match   9543 1451
 the available experimental data.                                 9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
  4.  Nubar and the fission neutron spectra were obtained using   9543 1451
  Madland-Nix theory.                                             9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
 II.  THEORETICAL ANALYSIS                                        9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    The primary goal of the theoretical analysis was to provide a 9543 1451
 consistent set of data for all reactions over the energy range   9543 1451
 30 keV to 30 MeV.  In the case of n+241Am, there are reasonable  9543 1451
 experimental data available for the neutron total and fission    9543 1451
 cross sections.  Therefore, the function of the theoretical      9543 1451
 analysis was to provide the elastic, inelastic, (n,2n), (n,3n)   9543 1451
 and (n,4n) cross sections, as well as the angular and energy     9543 1451
 distributions of secondary neutrons.  To accomplish this, a      9543 1451
 theoretical analysis was performed, adjusting the relevant       9543 1451
 parameters to match the total, fission, and (n,g) cross          9543 1451
 sections.  Additionally, a theoretical analysis was performed to 9543 1451
 obtain the average neutron multiplicity from fission and the     9543 1451
 energy spectra of fission neutrons as a function of incident     9543 1451
 energy.                                                          9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    Coupled-channel deformed optical model calculations were      9543 1451
 performed with the ECIS code (Ra70) over the incident neutron    9543 1451
 energy range from 0.001 to 30 MeV.  Hauser-Feshbach reaction     9543 1451
 theory calculations were carried out with the LANL version of    9543 1451
 the COMNUC code (Du70) at lower energies and the GNASH           9543 1451
 statistical/preequilibrium code (Yo92)  at higher energies to    9543 1451
 obtain all partial reaction cross section data.  Both reaction   9543 1451
 theory codes used neutron transmission coefficients from the     9543 1451
 optical model analysis.                                          9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    A.  Optical Model                                             9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    The optical model potential was obtained by considering       9543 1451
 several coupled-channel parameterizations developed from n +     9543 1451
 235,238U and 239Pu experimental data (Ma78, Yo88, Yo92a).        9543 1451
 Parameters were adjusted until a reasonable fit to experimental  9543 1451
 data for the neutron total cross section of 241Am was obtained.  9543 1451
 The lowest five members of the 5/2- ground state rotational band 9543 1451
 were included in the calculations, that is, the 7/2-, 9/2-,      9543 1451
 11/2- and 13/2-  excited states at Ex = 41, 94, 159 and 235 keV  9543 1451
 were coupled with the 5/2- ground state.                         9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    B.  Reaction Theory Calculations                              9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    The Hauser-Feshbach statistical calculations were performed   9543 1451
 with the COMNUC (Du70) and GNASH (Yo92b) codes.  Both codes      9543 1451
 include a double-humped fission barrier model, using uncoupled   9543 1451
 oscillators for the barrier representation in GNASH and coupled  9543 1451
 or uncoupled oscillators in COMNUC, as described by Arthur       9543 1451
 (Ar82a).  The COMNUC calculations include the possibility of     9543 1451
 width-fluctuation corrections and corrections for class II       9543 1451
 fluctuations (Ly74), which are needed at lower energies, whereas 9543 1451
 GNASH provides the preequilibrium corrections that are required  9543 1451
 at higher energies.  Accordingly, COMNUC was used in the         9543 1451
 calculations below about 2 MeV, utilizing a non-resonant model   9543 1451
 and including class II fluctuations, and the GNASH code was      9543 1451
 employed at higher energies using two uncoupled oscillators in   9543 1451
 the fission calculations.                                        9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    Each compound nucleus formed in the calculations is permitted 9543 1451
 to decay through the fission channel, by neutron emission, and   9543 1451
 by gamma-ray emission.  Neutron transmission coefficients for    9543 1451
 the Hauser-Feshbach calculations are obtained from the coupled-  9543 1451
 channel optical model.  Gamma ray transmission coefficients are  9543 1451
 obtained from gamma-ray strength functions calculated with the   9543 1451
 generalized Lorentzian model of Kopecky and Uhl (Ko90).          9543 1451
 Transmission coefficients for fission are calculated from the    9543 1451
 fission model summarized here and detailed in Yo92b.             9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    Gilbert and Cameron (Gi70) phenomenological level density     9543 1451
 functions were used to represent continuum levels at ground-     9543 1451
 state deformations, appropriately matched to available           9543 1451
 experimental structure data at lower excitation energies.        9543 1451
 Multiplicative factors were applied to the level density         9543 1451
 functions to account for enhancements in the fission transition  9543 1451
 state densities at the fission barriers due to increased         9543 1451
 asymmetry conditions, and the continuum level densities were     9543 1451
 matched to the discrete fission transition states at each        9543 1451
 barrier.   The discrete fission transition state spectra were    9543 1451
 calculated from bandhead information taken from calculations and 9543 1451
 compilations by Britt (Br82) and by Nagel (Na91).                9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
 III.  DESCRIPTION OF EVALUATED DATA BASE                         9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    A.  Total Cross Section                                       9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    The evaluated total cross section below 30 keV is obtained    9543 1451
 from the resonance parameter evaluation in ENDF/B-VI, suitably   9543 1451
 matched to the results of the current analysis at 30 keV.  From  9543 1451
 30 keV to 30 MeV, the coupled-channel deformed optical model     9543 1451
 calculations described above were modified to agree with the     9543 1451
 experimental data of Phillips (Ph70).                            9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    B.  Elastic Cross Section                                     9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    The elastic cross section at all energies is obtained from    9543 1451
 the difference of the total and nonelastic cross sections.       9543 1451
 Below 30 keV it comes from the ENDF/B-VI resonance parameters    9543 1451
 and at higher energies it is mainly determined by the coupled-   9543 1451
 channel optical model calculations.  Angular distributions for   9543 1451
 elastic neutrons were obtained at all energies from the coupled- 9543 1451
 channel calculations and are given as Legendre expansions.       9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    C.  Fission Cross Section                                     9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    The fission cross section was obtained by adjusting the       9543 1451
 results of the theoretical analysis to optimize agreement with   9543 1451
 experimental data.  At most energies the adjustment was less     9543 1451
 than a few percent.  Above 8 MeV, the theoretical values were    9543 1451
 used directly.  Neutrons from fission are assumed to isotropic   9543 1451
 in the laboratory system.                                        9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    D.  Radiative Capture Cross Section                           9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    The radiative capture cross section is calculated using the   9543 1451
 generalized Lorentzian model of Ko90.  The normalization of the  9543 1451
 strength function was set by requiring the calculated (n,g)      9543 1451
 cross section be consistent with measured values for 241Am.      9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    E.  Inelastic Neutron Cross Sections                          9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    Discrete (n,n') cross sections are included for the lowest 40 9543 1451
 excited states of 241Am.  The first, second, third,  and fifth   9543 1451
 excited states are members of the K = 5/2 ground-state           9543 1451
 rotational band and include coupled-channel as well as compound  9543 1451
 nucleus contributions.  The remaining discrete-state cross       9543 1451
 sections through the 40th excited state are combinations of      9543 1451
 compound nucleus and preequilibrium contributions and were       9543 1451
 calculated with the GNASH code.  Angular distributions for all   9543 1451
 the discrete inelastic neutrons are appropriate combinations of  9543 1451
 the compound nucleus, direct reaction, and preequilibrium        9543 1451
 contributions and are represented by Legendre expansions.        9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    The inelastic data corresponding to excitation energies in    9543 1451
 241Am above 0.508 MeV are given as energy-angle correlated       9543 1451
 continuous spectra and were calculated with the GNASH code.  The 9543 1451
 results are given in File 6 of the ENDF/B-formatted evaluation   9543 1451
 (ENDF-6 format) and utilize systematics by Kalbach (Ka88) for    9543 1451
 angular distribution information, parameterized in terms of      9543 1451
 preequilibrium ratios calculated in GNASH.                       9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    F.  Cross Sections for 241Am(n,xn) Reactions                  9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    The 241Am(n,2n), (n,3n), and (n,4n) cross sections result     9543 1451
 entirely from the theoretical analysis and GNASH calculations.   9543 1451
 Energy-angle correlated distributions are given for all the      9543 1451
 241Am(n,xn) reactions, making use of Kalbach's systematics       9543 1451
 (Ka88) and the ENDF-6 File 6 representation.                     9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    G.  Nubar                                                     9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    The evaluation of delayed nubar was carried over directly     9543 1451
 from the ENDF/B-VI evaluation of 241Am.  The prompt nubar        9543 1451
 evaluation was obtained using Madland-Nix theory.                9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    H.  Fission Neutron Spectra                                   9543 1451
                                                                  9543 1451
    The fission neutron spectra was determined using Madland-Nix  9543 1451
 theory and are consistent with nubar.                            9543 1451
